It can be easy to get caught up at times with wanting to lift heavy, but more often than not the greatest gains will come when operating at less exciting sub-max rep ranges, where you can get through plenty of volume, refine your skill & practice technique. Squatting, bench-pressing and deadlifting in particular are highly difficult skills to master, so it doesn’t make a lot of sense to be consistently lifting as heavy as possible for only a few reps each week.
-
While heavy lifting obviously has it’s place within in strength or hypertrophy based training program, don’t discount the grunt work. Volume sets are your biggest bang-for-buck offerings when it comes to adding to total training volume, creating work capacity (the opportunity to increase intensity/ load in the future) & building muscle which in turn will help you with getting stronger. Fight the urge to load all the plates & do your best to stay away from absolute failure - it’s only going to lead to a reduction in training volume & decrease in performance over time.
-
Monday’s workout began with 5 x 10 x 165kg (363lb) with no belt (cardio). I can lift a hell of a lot more than this, but I want to make progress in the gym, lift more and more over time, progressively overload my muscles with more and more work & refine my skill, so it makes more sense given I’m not currently preparing for a powerlifting meet/ strength-based event to work at well below my strength capacity to do so. Lifting without a belt also means I’m having to work harder at such a weight & use my back & core far more, something that will carry over directly into heavier work with a belt later on.
-
SET UP: Feet under hips under bar. Unrack (hip extension). Allow the bar to settle. Three step walkout, adjust feet if necessary. Big belly breath. Brace core (think about someone punching you in the stomach). Pull bar down HARD onto back. Start slow, then fast into & out of the hole. Push back through the bar. No breathing while bar actively moving. Reset, go again. Every rep is a separate event - treat each squat as a 1RM & you’ll never have an issue with adding load again. #TeamNCF
